People distrust models,
because they don't understand.

00:44:57.150 --> 00:44:58.870
We've heard recently
the news, of course,

00:44:58.870 --> 00:45:00.411
this thing about
economic forecasters

00:45:00.411 --> 00:45:02.140
have no idea what
they're talking about.

00:45:02.140 --> 00:45:05.020
I used to be an economic
forecaster, and yeah.

00:45:05.020 --> 00:45:09.040
There are models, and
they're very good models.

00:45:09.040 --> 00:45:10.990
The treasury, for
example, in the UK

00:45:10.990 --> 00:45:12.570
employs hundreds of people.

00:45:12.570 --> 00:45:14.695
They're programming and
coming up with these things

00:45:14.695 --> 00:45:16.820
and testing them and
constant;y changing them,

00:45:16.820 --> 00:45:18.434
as does the Bank of England.

00:45:18.434 --> 00:45:21.100
But I also know-- having been an
economist and worked with these

00:45:21.100 --> 00:45:21.880
models--

00:45:21.880 --> 00:45:25.360
that what you get out
depends on what you put in.

00:45:25.360 --> 00:45:27.370
So you can make
various assumptions,

00:45:27.370 --> 00:45:29.830
and that will impact
on what you get out.

00:45:29.830 --> 00:45:33.730
So I'm a little bit cautious
sometimes about extolling

00:45:33.730 --> 00:45:35.510
the virtues of models too much.

00:45:37.371 --> 00:45:39.120
AUDIENCE: You painted
a very lucid picture

00:45:39.120 --> 00:45:42.030
about how complicated
the global system is.

00:45:42.030 --> 00:45:45.076
But obviously, 2008, 2007
showed that economists

00:45:45.076 --> 00:45:46.200
don't have all the answers.

00:45:46.200 --> 00:45:49.630
Do you still trust economists--
macroeconomists specifically--

00:45:49.630 --> 00:45:51.657
and a little bit
more information

00:45:51.657 --> 00:45:52.490
around those models?

00:45:52.490 --> 00:45:53.690
And are we perhaps
measuring the right thing?

00:45:53.690 --> 00:45:54.600
I can't remember off
the top of my head--

00:45:54.600 --> 00:45:56.970
there was a conversation
recently about GDP

00:45:56.970 --> 00:45:59.880
not measuring a certain aspect
of the productive economy

00:45:59.880 --> 00:46:01.740
and incorporating
new things into it.

00:46:01.740 --> 00:46:03.323
I guess just your
thoughts around that

00:46:03.323 --> 00:46:04.560
would be interesting.

00:46:04.560 --> 00:46:08.250
DHARSHINI DAVID: Do
I trust economists?

00:46:08.250 --> 00:46:10.440
Good question.

00:46:10.440 --> 00:46:13.270
I think it's a bit like being
an astrologer or a weather

00:46:13.270 --> 00:46:15.330
forecaster, isn't it
to a certain point?

00:46:15.330 --> 00:46:17.371
You get a lot of bad press
when you get it wrong,

00:46:17.371 --> 00:46:19.515
and it's easy to get it wrong.

00:46:19.515 --> 00:46:21.980
And there's all those jokes
about economists in a room,

00:46:21.980 --> 00:46:25.230
and you get more views
than there are economists.

00:46:25.230 --> 00:46:27.319
I think in terms of
analyzing the facts--

00:46:27.319 --> 00:46:28.860
And I think an
economist's job should

00:46:28.860 --> 00:46:33.020
be to pull apart the facts,
see the underlying picture.

00:46:33.020 --> 00:46:35.100
What we found in recent
years in particular

00:46:35.100 --> 00:46:38.100
is that politics
personalities tend

00:46:38.100 --> 00:46:40.920
to obscure those facts
and the underlying trends.

00:46:40.920 --> 00:46:42.420
I think economists
could do a better

00:46:42.420 --> 00:46:44.130
job in bringing those to light.

00:46:44.130 --> 00:46:45.840
When it comes to
protecting things,

00:46:45.840 --> 00:46:48.810
I think we got a little bit
too complacent about looking

00:46:48.810 --> 00:46:49.960
at the past.

00:46:49.960 --> 00:46:51.930
And a lot of economists
who were working

00:46:51.930 --> 00:46:54.510
around the time the financial
crisis quite honestly

00:46:54.510 --> 00:46:57.516
had never seen a
proper recession.

00:46:57.516 --> 00:46:58.890
You'd have to go
back to the '70s

00:46:58.890 --> 00:47:00.547
to see a really
sharp economic shock.

00:47:00.547 --> 00:47:02.880
They just weren't used to it,
and the models had kind of

00:47:02.880 --> 00:47:05.460
got a bit complacent too.

00:47:05.460 --> 00:47:08.250
And you mentioned the GDP.

00:47:08.250 --> 00:47:09.690
This is a really
interesting point

00:47:09.690 --> 00:47:12.290
about whether we measure
the world's well being

00:47:12.290 --> 00:47:14.880
in forms of the amount of
income we can generate,

00:47:14.880 --> 00:47:17.155
and there's much
more to the picture.

00:47:17.155 --> 00:47:18.780
That measurement of
income doesn't take

00:47:18.780 --> 00:47:19.770
account of a lot of things.

00:47:19.770 --> 00:47:21.228
It doesn't take
account of the fact

00:47:21.228 --> 00:47:23.670
that you might go home
after a 12-hour day,

00:47:23.670 --> 00:47:26.350
and you've still got a whole
lot of DIY to do or housework

00:47:26.350 --> 00:47:26.850
or whatever.

00:47:26.850 --> 00:47:28.380
None of that counts.

00:47:28.380 --> 00:47:31.790
There's a famous example of
if you marry your cleaner,

00:47:31.790 --> 00:47:35.040
you're reducing GDP.

00:47:35.040 --> 00:47:37.530
Because before that,
the cleaner's output

00:47:37.530 --> 00:47:40.030
classed as part of GDP.

00:47:40.030 --> 00:47:44.570
Marry the cleaner and it's just
counted as domestic work, which

00:47:44.570 --> 00:47:45.840
doesn't show up.

00:47:45.840 --> 00:47:49.964
Also, GDP doesn't measure things
like environmental impact.

00:47:49.964 --> 00:47:52.380
Technological change-- which
is one of the things that was

00:47:52.380 --> 00:47:53.790
written about recently--

00:47:53.790 --> 00:47:56.460
is the fact that when
you look at GDP measures,

00:47:56.460 --> 00:47:58.380
they haven't taken
account the way

00:47:58.380 --> 00:48:00.614
that technology's
moved in recent years.

00:48:00.614 --> 00:48:02.030
And therefore, in
many ways, we're

00:48:02.030 --> 00:48:05.180
underestimating the health
of the global economy.

00:48:05.180 --> 00:48:07.180
So there's a lot more
work to be done on that.

00:48:07.180 --> 00:48:08.970
And I think it's
something that now

00:48:08.970 --> 00:48:12.990
we've got past the seismic
shocks of the financial crisis,

00:48:12.990 --> 00:48:15.722
central banks are finally
waking up and paying attention.

00:48:19.539 --> 00:48:20.080
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:48:20.080 --> 00:48:22.690
When you give out a loan, you
have some kind of expectation

00:48:22.690 --> 00:48:25.310
that you get the money back.

00:48:25.310 --> 00:48:29.830
But given that countries
have such a big debt--

00:48:29.830 --> 00:48:30.970
in particular, the US--

00:48:30.970 --> 00:48:33.570
why does it not all collapse?

00:48:33.570 --> 00:48:36.314
Is it feasible that you
can get the money back?

00:48:36.314 --> 00:48:37.855
DHARSHINI DAVID: I
don't know if it's

00:48:37.855 --> 00:48:40.179
feasible you can
get the money back.

00:48:40.179 --> 00:48:42.220
America's counting the
fact that everyone wants--

00:48:42.220 --> 00:48:44.830
America in particular
is counting on the fact

00:48:44.830 --> 00:48:48.480
that everyone wants dollars
to trade and to keep

00:48:48.480 --> 00:48:51.730
in bank reserves, and that's
why it can sell those bonds.

00:48:51.730 --> 00:48:53.950
That's why it can
fund its deficits

00:48:53.950 --> 00:48:57.490
and ultimately its debts.

00:48:57.490 --> 00:49:02.170
It means that America is seen
as being good for the money.

00:49:02.170 --> 00:49:06.040
If China and Japan got together
and said, what do you think.

00:49:06.040 --> 00:49:07.710
Should we ask for
our money back?

00:49:07.710 --> 00:49:09.830
That could undermine
the economy.

00:49:09.830 --> 00:49:12.610
It's one reason why the
yen has never taken off

00:49:12.610 --> 00:49:16.480
in a big way as a
major reserve currency,

00:49:16.480 --> 00:49:18.910
because investors
around the globe

00:49:18.910 --> 00:49:23.050
have been so concerned about
the state of the amount of debt

00:49:23.050 --> 00:49:27.220
Japan has that they don't see
as being a stable and therefore

00:49:27.220 --> 00:49:28.820
ultimately attractive economy.

00:49:28.820 --> 00:49:31.450
But because the dollar has a
special status because it's

00:49:31.450 --> 00:49:33.150
required for other
things, America

00:49:33.150 --> 00:49:34.316
doesn't suffer that problem.

00:49:38.618 --> 00:49:41.300
SPEAKER: I'll go with one
more, and then we'll round off.

00:49:41.300 --> 00:49:42.360
What do you think--

00:49:42.360 --> 00:49:46.691
so outside of Brexit, what's
perhaps the next big thing

00:49:46.691 --> 00:49:49.190
coming down the line that we
should be aware of that perhaps

00:49:49.190 --> 00:49:50.260
people aren't?

00:49:50.260 --> 00:49:52.010
Is it aging population?

00:49:52.010 --> 00:49:56.160
Is it unforeseen tech--

00:49:56.160 --> 00:49:57.220
AI [INAUDIBLE]?

00:49:57.220 --> 00:50:00.124
What's front of your mind that
we should be thinking about?

00:50:00.124 --> 00:50:01.040
DHARSHINI DAVID: Yeah.

00:50:01.040 --> 00:50:02.780
I had something up there
about aging population

00:50:02.780 --> 00:50:04.238
which I didn't talk
about because I

00:50:04.238 --> 00:50:06.020
was conscious of time.

00:50:06.020 --> 00:50:08.450
As we're talking right
here, Philip Hammond

00:50:08.450 --> 00:50:10.900
is on his feet talking about
the state of public finances

00:50:10.900 --> 00:50:12.587
here in the UK.

00:50:12.587 --> 00:50:14.420
He's talking about the
next couple of years.

00:50:14.420 --> 00:50:17.720
But to me, the big problem
that's looming for all of us

00:50:17.720 --> 00:50:20.540
is the fact that
populations are aging.

00:50:20.540 --> 00:50:23.870
And that puts a whole
different kind of emphasis

00:50:23.870 --> 00:50:26.780
on the finances we have-- public
finances and private finances

00:50:26.780 --> 00:50:28.960
and the way we live,
the way we work,

00:50:28.960 --> 00:50:31.130
and the way we fund everything.

00:50:31.130 --> 00:50:34.159
I don't think any
government has really

00:50:34.159 --> 00:50:35.200
thought that one through.

00:50:35.200 --> 00:50:37.850
And every time they try to,
they stick a toe in the water.

00:50:37.850 --> 00:50:40.010
Things like dementia
tax, of course--

00:50:40.010 --> 00:50:41.150
hugely controversial.

00:50:41.150 --> 00:50:45.344
But there is a valid
issue hiding under all

00:50:45.344 --> 00:50:47.510
that-- that somehow we're
going to think of the fact

00:50:47.510 --> 00:50:50.630
that the average person
who's over 64 costs

00:50:50.630 --> 00:50:52.230
four times as much
in health care

00:50:52.230 --> 00:50:54.256
as someone under the age of 16.

00:50:54.256 --> 00:50:56.130
And someone's going to
have to pay that bill.

00:50:56.130 --> 00:50:57.255
We're going to live longer.

00:50:57.255 --> 00:50:59.635
We're going to live better
and longer hopefully,

00:50:59.635 --> 00:51:00.805
but how do we pay for that?

00:51:00.805 --> 00:51:02.180
And I think that's
something that

00:51:02.180 --> 00:51:03.770
has to be the subject
of much debate.

00:51:03.770 --> 00:51:06.228
And hopefully them at Davos
might get their heads around it

00:51:06.228 --> 00:51:06.894
as well.

